00:00:26.436 --> 00:00:27.406 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hi, everyone.

00:00:27.646 --> 00:00:29.246 A:middle
My name's Paul Salzman, and my

00:00:29.246 --> 00:00:30.636 A:middle
friend Josh Ford and I are very

00:00:30.636 --> 00:00:31.706 A:middle
excited to talk to you today

00:00:32.016 --> 00:00:33.066 A:middle
about servicing your Siri

00:00:33.066 --> 00:00:34.276 A:middle
shortcuts on the Siri watch

00:00:34.276 --> 00:00:34.626 A:middle
face.

00:00:36.316 --> 00:00:37.556 A:middle
Last year, we released the Siri

00:00:37.556 --> 00:00:39.276 A:middle
watch face, which has glanceable

00:00:39.276 --> 00:00:40.486 A:middle
information and tappable

00:00:40.486 --> 00:00:41.686 A:middle
actions, sorted by their

00:00:41.686 --> 00:00:43.056 A:middle
relevance to the user, at every

00:00:43.056 --> 00:00:43.516 A:middle
wrist raise.

00:00:44.376 --> 00:00:45.786 A:middle
That means our users have access

00:00:45.786 --> 00:00:47.326 A:middle
to dynamically updated content,

00:00:47.676 --> 00:00:48.646 A:middle
relevant to them throughout the

00:00:48.646 --> 00:00:50.006 A:middle
day without any configuration

00:00:50.006 --> 00:00:50.436 A:middle
required.

00:00:51.746 --> 00:00:53.046 A:middle
And now, in watchOS 5, we are

00:00:53.046 --> 00:00:54.466 A:middle
very excited to add your

00:00:54.466 --> 00:00:55.936 A:middle
applications as data sources to

00:00:55.936 --> 00:00:56.766 A:middle
the Siri watch face.

00:00:58.196 --> 00:00:59.666 A:middle
The shortcuts you provide will

00:00:59.666 --> 00:01:00.566 A:middle
show up on the watch face, on

00:00:59.666 --> 00:01:00.566 A:middle
show up on the watch face, on

00:01:00.566 --> 00:01:01.376 A:middle
these items that we call

00:01:01.376 --> 00:01:01.876 A:middle
platters.

00:01:02.276 --> 00:01:03.436 A:middle
When the user taps on one of

00:01:03.436 --> 00:01:04.825 A:middle
these platters, the underlying

00:01:04.825 --> 00:01:05.916 A:middle
shortcut will be executed.

00:01:06.256 --> 00:01:07.486 A:middle
That can do something like

00:01:07.996 --> 00:01:09.036 A:middle
launching into your application

00:01:09.086 --> 00:01:12.246 A:middle
into a specific context, or if

00:01:12.246 --> 00:01:13.006 A:middle
your shortcut supports

00:01:13.006 --> 00:01:15.216 A:middle
background execution, we can run

00:01:15.216 --> 00:01:16.566 A:middle
that inline on the watch face.

00:01:17.586 --> 00:01:18.396 A:middle
That means users can take

00:01:18.396 --> 00:01:19.496 A:middle
advantage of your application's

00:01:19.496 --> 00:01:20.806 A:middle
functionality without leaving

00:01:20.806 --> 00:01:21.446 A:middle
their watch face.

00:01:22.006 --> 00:01:23.146 A:middle
So, let's take a look at what

00:01:23.146 --> 00:01:24.276 A:middle
we're going to talk about today.

00:01:24.596 --> 00:01:25.686 A:middle
We're going to start off by

00:01:25.686 --> 00:01:27.066 A:middle
going over how content appears

00:01:27.066 --> 00:01:27.926 A:middle
on the Siri watch face.

00:01:29.246 --> 00:01:30.366 A:middle
After that, we'll talk about the

00:01:30.366 --> 00:01:32.056 A:middle
Relevant Shortcut API, which is

00:01:32.056 --> 00:01:33.266 A:middle
the API you use to provide

00:01:33.266 --> 00:01:34.486 A:middle
content to the Siri watch face.

00:01:35.846 --> 00:01:37.166 A:middle
We'll also go over how you can

00:01:37.166 --> 00:01:38.636 A:middle
use this API within your iOS

00:01:38.636 --> 00:01:39.926 A:middle
application to provide content

00:01:39.926 --> 00:01:40.756 A:middle
to the Siri watch face.

00:01:40.826 --> 00:01:42.416 A:middle
And then, I'm going to hand

00:01:42.416 --> 00:01:43.896 A:middle
things over to Josh, who'll talk

00:01:43.896 --> 00:01:45.536 A:middle
about our prediction engine, as

00:01:45.536 --> 00:01:46.866 A:middle
well as give you insight as to

00:01:46.866 --> 00:01:48.346 A:middle
how best to use these API's for

00:01:48.346 --> 00:01:49.066 A:middle
your application.

00:01:49.666 --> 00:01:52.536 A:middle
So, let's talk about how content

00:01:52.536 --> 00:01:53.726 A:middle
appears on the Siri watch face.

00:01:55.246 --> 00:01:56.116 A:middle
Everything on the Siri watch

00:01:56.116 --> 00:01:57.716 A:middle
face is sorted by its relevance

00:01:57.716 --> 00:01:58.206 A:middle
to the user.

00:01:58.836 --> 00:01:59.746 A:middle
The more relevant a piece of

00:01:59.746 --> 00:02:01.306 A:middle
content is, the higher up on the

00:01:59.746 --> 00:02:01.306 A:middle
content is, the higher up on the

00:02:01.306 --> 00:02:02.386 A:middle
watch face it's going to appear.

00:02:03.076 --> 00:02:04.196 A:middle
And, we calculate relevance by

00:02:04.196 --> 00:02:05.936 A:middle
incorporating a number of inputs

00:02:05.936 --> 00:02:07.286 A:middle
across the system, like the

00:02:07.286 --> 00:02:08.776 A:middle
current time of day, the user's

00:02:08.776 --> 00:02:10.446 A:middle
location, their routine, and

00:02:10.446 --> 00:02:11.546 A:middle
their engagement with a given

00:02:11.546 --> 00:02:12.136 A:middle
data source.

00:02:13.546 --> 00:02:14.596 A:middle
You'll provide this content to

00:02:14.596 --> 00:02:15.946 A:middle
us with a relevantShortcut,

00:02:16.366 --> 00:02:18.346 A:middle
which associates a shortcut with

00:02:18.346 --> 00:02:19.576 A:middle
UI customization, and the

00:02:19.576 --> 00:02:20.626 A:middle
ability to give us hints as to

00:02:20.626 --> 00:02:21.786 A:middle
when to deploy your content.

00:02:22.996 --> 00:02:24.796 A:middle
Now, we will derive implicit

00:02:24.796 --> 00:02:25.876 A:middle
relevance for the shortcuts you

00:02:25.876 --> 00:02:27.426 A:middle
provide based off of your user's

00:02:27.426 --> 00:02:28.556 A:middle
past interaction with the

00:02:28.556 --> 00:02:29.106 A:middle
shortcuts.

00:02:29.646 --> 00:02:31.036 A:middle
But, often you have much more

00:02:31.036 --> 00:02:32.116 A:middle
insightful suggestions,

00:02:32.406 --> 00:02:33.146 A:middle
especially when showing

00:02:33.146 --> 00:02:34.606 A:middle
glanceable information, or if

00:02:34.606 --> 00:02:35.626 A:middle
you want to suggest a shortcut

00:02:35.656 --> 00:02:36.836 A:middle
that hasn't yet been executed by

00:02:36.836 --> 00:02:37.206 A:middle
a user.

00:02:37.306 --> 00:02:38.466 A:middle
So, you can provide us things

00:02:38.466 --> 00:02:39.466 A:middle
called relevance providers.

00:02:40.786 --> 00:02:41.866 A:middle
And, just like a first-party

00:02:41.866 --> 00:02:43.756 A:middle
data source, users can disable

00:02:43.786 --> 00:02:46.036 A:middle
or re-enable your data source in

00:02:46.036 --> 00:02:47.536 A:middle
the Siri face customization page

00:02:47.586 --> 00:02:49.126 A:middle
in the iOS Watch app.

00:02:49.876 --> 00:02:51.726 A:middle
Now, before we get too far into

00:02:51.726 --> 00:02:52.736 A:middle
adopting the Relevant Shortcut

00:02:52.736 --> 00:02:54.276 A:middle
API, we want to make sure we're

00:02:54.276 --> 00:02:55.146 A:middle
not contending with these

00:02:55.146 --> 00:02:56.676 A:middle
relevance calculations when we

00:02:56.676 --> 00:02:58.216 A:middle
see how our relevant shortcuts

00:02:58.396 --> 00:02:59.546 A:middle
behave and look on the watch

00:02:59.546 --> 00:02:59.916 A:middle
face.

00:03:00.766 --> 00:03:01.736 A:middle
So, while we're developing,

00:03:01.766 --> 00:03:02.796 A:middle
we're going to want to go into

00:03:02.796 --> 00:03:04.096 A:middle
the iOS Settings app, into the

00:03:04.096 --> 00:03:06.296 A:middle
Developer's page, and find the

00:03:06.296 --> 00:03:07.456 A:middle
Shortcuts Testing section.

00:03:07.996 --> 00:03:10.456 A:middle
In there, we can ensure that our

00:03:10.456 --> 00:03:11.906 A:middle
most recently provided relevant

00:03:11.906 --> 00:03:13.376 A:middle
shortcuts show up at the top of

00:03:13.376 --> 00:03:15.216 A:middle
the watch face, by enabling the

00:03:15.216 --> 00:03:16.626 A:middle
Show Recent Shortcuts option.

00:03:19.796 --> 00:03:21.616 A:middle
Additionally, as we get further

00:03:21.616 --> 00:03:23.146 A:middle
into adopting this API in our

00:03:23.146 --> 00:03:25.216 A:middle
iOS application, we can cause

00:03:25.216 --> 00:03:26.666 A:middle
the periodic syncing of relevant

00:03:26.666 --> 00:03:28.346 A:middle
shortcuts from the iOS device to

00:03:28.346 --> 00:03:29.816 A:middle
the watch to occur immediately

00:03:29.816 --> 00:03:30.816 A:middle
by tapping the Force Sync

00:03:30.816 --> 00:03:31.866 A:middle
Shortcuts to Watch button.

00:03:32.286 --> 00:03:34.616 A:middle
So, now let's talk about

00:03:34.616 --> 00:03:36.426 A:middle
relevant shortcuts, and at the

00:03:36.426 --> 00:03:37.846 A:middle
core of a relevant shortcut, is

00:03:37.846 --> 00:03:38.286 A:middle
a shortcut.

00:03:39.356 --> 00:03:40.706 A:middle
Shortcuts encompass key

00:03:40.706 --> 00:03:42.016 A:middle
functionality, within your

00:03:42.016 --> 00:03:43.116 A:middle
application, that you want to

00:03:43.116 --> 00:03:44.226 A:middle
make more accessible to your

00:03:44.226 --> 00:03:44.606 A:middle
users.

00:03:45.336 --> 00:03:46.126 A:middle
And, they can access these

00:03:46.126 --> 00:03:47.336 A:middle
shortcuts by saying key phrases

00:03:47.336 --> 00:03:49.066 A:middle
into Siri, or tapping on various

00:03:49.066 --> 00:03:49.476 A:middle
system UI.

00:03:49.476 --> 00:03:51.236 A:middle
And, in the case of watchOS,

00:03:51.446 --> 00:03:52.376 A:middle
that's a platter on the Siri

00:03:52.376 --> 00:03:53.606 A:middle
watch face.

00:03:54.196 --> 00:03:55.626 A:middle
There's a lot of in-depth

00:03:55.626 --> 00:03:56.636 A:middle
discussion about how to make

00:03:56.686 --> 00:03:57.596 A:middle
great shortcuts this year.

00:03:57.656 --> 00:03:58.896 A:middle
And all will give a high-level

00:03:58.896 --> 00:04:00.526 A:middle
overview of how they work with a

00:03:58.896 --> 00:04:00.526 A:middle
overview of how they work with a

00:04:00.526 --> 00:04:01.526 A:middle
watchOS persecutive.

00:04:01.646 --> 00:04:02.946 A:middle
I highly recommend seeing the

00:04:02.946 --> 00:04:04.246 A:middle
"Introduction to Siri Shortcuts"

00:04:04.276 --> 00:04:05.716 A:middle
talk, and the "Building for

00:04:05.936 --> 00:04:07.356 A:middle
Voice with Siri Shortcuts" that

00:04:07.356 --> 00:04:08.046 A:middle
happened earlier in the

00:04:08.046 --> 00:04:08.626 A:middle
conference.

00:04:10.236 --> 00:04:11.646 A:middle
So, shortcuts can be made out of

00:04:11.646 --> 00:04:12.506 A:middle
one of two things.

00:04:13.306 --> 00:04:14.686 A:middle
An NSUserActivity, which

00:04:14.716 --> 00:04:15.836 A:middle
represents a state within your

00:04:15.836 --> 00:04:16.706 A:middle
application you want to

00:04:16.706 --> 00:04:19.096 A:middle
accelerate users back into, or

00:04:19.096 --> 00:04:20.796 A:middle
an intent, which can execute a

00:04:20.796 --> 00:04:22.166 A:middle
task on your user's behalf.

00:04:23.126 --> 00:04:23.886 A:middle
Now, intents are really

00:04:23.886 --> 00:04:24.876 A:middle
powerful, because they can

00:04:24.876 --> 00:04:26.076 A:middle
support background execution,

00:04:26.526 --> 00:04:27.676 A:middle
which means that users can take

00:04:27.676 --> 00:04:28.866 A:middle
advantage of your functionality

00:04:28.996 --> 00:04:29.956 A:middle
without having to launch your

00:04:29.956 --> 00:04:30.736 A:middle
app into the foreground.

00:04:31.376 --> 00:04:32.696 A:middle
In fact, users can request

00:04:32.696 --> 00:04:34.256 A:middle
background-capable intents that

00:04:34.256 --> 00:04:35.226 A:middle
are available on their iPhone

00:04:35.376 --> 00:04:36.266 A:middle
from their Apple watch or

00:04:36.266 --> 00:04:36.706 A:middle
HomePod.

00:04:37.986 --> 00:04:39.086 A:middle
And, our frameworks provide a

00:04:39.086 --> 00:04:40.316 A:middle
lot of built-in intents you can

00:04:40.316 --> 00:04:41.386 A:middle
take advantage of right now,

00:04:41.806 --> 00:04:43.236 A:middle
like sending a message, starting

00:04:43.236 --> 00:04:44.606 A:middle
a workout, or requesting a ride.

00:04:45.336 --> 00:04:46.916 A:middle
But, new in watchOS 5, and iOS

00:04:46.916 --> 00:04:48.626 A:middle
12, you can make your own custom

00:04:48.626 --> 00:04:49.666 A:middle
intents that have the

00:04:49.666 --> 00:04:51.056 A:middle
functionality that your app does

00:04:51.106 --> 00:04:51.426 A:middle
best.

00:04:52.436 --> 00:04:53.836 A:middle
There's this awesome in-depth

00:04:53.836 --> 00:04:55.616 A:middle
intents definition file and

00:04:55.616 --> 00:04:56.736 A:middle
editor built into Xcode.

00:04:56.886 --> 00:04:57.906 A:middle
And, I'll give you a couple of

00:04:57.906 --> 00:04:58.886 A:middle
pointers related to relevant

00:04:58.886 --> 00:04:59.386 A:middle
shortcuts.

00:04:59.626 --> 00:05:00.496 A:middle
But, I highly recommend seeing

00:04:59.626 --> 00:05:00.496 A:middle
But, I highly recommend seeing

00:05:00.496 --> 00:05:01.836 A:middle
those other talks for full

00:05:02.436 --> 00:05:02.646 A:middle
details.

00:05:03.216 --> 00:05:04.766 A:middle
Now, let's go over a couple of

00:05:04.766 --> 00:05:06.346 A:middle
examples of how shortcuts will

00:05:06.346 --> 00:05:07.666 A:middle
execute when requested from a

00:05:07.666 --> 00:05:09.316 A:middle
watch app.

00:05:09.626 --> 00:05:12.016 A:middle
User generates their shortcut

00:05:12.016 --> 00:05:13.806 A:middle
request by tapping on the Siri

00:05:13.806 --> 00:05:15.056 A:middle
watch face, or by saying a key

00:05:15.056 --> 00:05:16.996 A:middle
voice phrase to Siri, and the

00:05:16.996 --> 00:05:18.206 A:middle
watch receives that request.

00:05:18.546 --> 00:05:19.816 A:middle
It'll examine it and determine,

00:05:19.876 --> 00:05:20.836 A:middle
is there an application that's

00:05:20.836 --> 00:05:21.886 A:middle
installed that can handle the

00:05:21.886 --> 00:05:22.336 A:middle
shortcut?

00:05:22.916 --> 00:05:24.306 A:middle
And, in this example, yes, there

00:05:24.306 --> 00:05:25.226 A:middle
is one that's installed.

00:05:25.626 --> 00:05:27.116 A:middle
So, we're going to dispatch that

00:05:27.116 --> 00:05:28.056 A:middle
shortcut to the appropriate

00:05:28.056 --> 00:05:28.656 A:middle
application.

00:05:29.496 --> 00:05:31.086 A:middle
If your shortcut is implemented

00:05:31.086 --> 00:05:32.346 A:middle
by an intent that can handle

00:05:32.346 --> 00:05:34.276 A:middle
background execution, the

00:05:34.276 --> 00:05:35.856 A:middle
application's intent execution

00:05:36.066 --> 00:05:36.876 A:middle
will run that shortcut.

00:05:37.486 --> 00:05:38.606 A:middle
But, if instead your shortcut is

00:05:38.606 --> 00:05:40.086 A:middle
built off of a NSUserActivity,

00:05:40.276 --> 00:05:41.206 A:middle
or an intent that can't run in

00:05:41.206 --> 00:05:42.616 A:middle
the background, the application

00:05:42.616 --> 00:05:43.836 A:middle
itself will be launched to

00:05:43.836 --> 00:05:44.546 A:middle
handle the shortcut.

00:05:45.586 --> 00:05:46.936 A:middle
When the shortcut execution is

00:05:46.936 --> 00:05:48.006 A:middle
complete, a result will be

00:05:48.006 --> 00:05:49.246 A:middle
generated, and then handed back

00:05:49.246 --> 00:05:49.666 A:middle
to the user.

00:05:50.856 --> 00:05:51.746 A:middle
Now, let's take a look at

00:05:51.746 --> 00:05:52.396 A:middle
another example.

00:05:53.036 --> 00:05:54.556 A:middle
In this case our user taps on

00:05:54.556 --> 00:05:55.556 A:middle
the Siri watch face, or says a

00:05:55.556 --> 00:05:57.056 A:middle
key phrase to Siri to generate

00:05:57.056 --> 00:05:58.416 A:middle
the shortcut request.

00:05:58.636 --> 00:06:00.216 A:middle
And, the watch will examine it.

00:05:58.636 --> 00:06:00.216 A:middle
And, the watch will examine it.

00:06:00.216 --> 00:06:01.646 A:middle
And, in this case, it'll

00:06:01.646 --> 00:06:02.626 A:middle
determine that there isn't an

00:06:02.626 --> 00:06:03.766 A:middle
application that's installed

00:06:03.846 --> 00:06:04.916 A:middle
that can handle the shortcut.

00:06:05.456 --> 00:06:06.556 A:middle
So, we'll check with the phone

00:06:06.556 --> 00:06:07.816 A:middle
and see if it has an app that

00:06:07.816 --> 00:06:08.576 A:middle
can handle the shortcut.

00:06:08.956 --> 00:06:10.316 A:middle
And, in this case, yes there is.

00:06:10.316 --> 00:06:11.306 A:middle
So, we're going to forward that

00:06:11.306 --> 00:06:12.496 A:middle
request over to the phone.

00:06:12.836 --> 00:06:14.216 A:middle
And, the proper application, or

00:06:14.216 --> 00:06:15.486 A:middle
intents extension will handle

00:06:15.486 --> 00:06:16.016 A:middle
execution.

00:06:16.546 --> 00:06:18.536 A:middle
When execution is complete, a

00:06:18.536 --> 00:06:19.676 A:middle
result will be generated on the

00:06:19.676 --> 00:06:21.156 A:middle
phone, and forward back to the

00:06:21.156 --> 00:06:22.336 A:middle
watch, and conveyed to the user.

00:06:22.336 --> 00:06:25.806 A:middle
So, now that we understand the

00:06:25.806 --> 00:06:26.946 A:middle
key concepts that make up a

00:06:26.946 --> 00:06:28.256 A:middle
shortcut, and how it'll execute

00:06:28.256 --> 00:06:29.446 A:middle
on the watch, let's talk about

00:06:29.446 --> 00:06:31.166 A:middle
relevant shortcuts, which take

00:06:31.166 --> 00:06:32.456 A:middle
your shortcuts and show them on

00:06:32.456 --> 00:06:33.376 A:middle
the watch face when they're most

00:06:33.376 --> 00:06:33.696 A:middle
relevant.

00:06:35.066 --> 00:06:36.466 A:middle
We can automatically populate

00:06:36.466 --> 00:06:37.756 A:middle
the fields on the platters on

00:06:37.756 --> 00:06:38.936 A:middle
the Siri watch face, based on

00:06:38.936 --> 00:06:39.846 A:middle
your shortcut content.

00:06:40.016 --> 00:06:41.706 A:middle
But, you can also customize the

00:06:41.706 --> 00:06:42.826 A:middle
platter's display, which is

00:06:42.826 --> 00:06:43.846 A:middle
really useful for displaying

00:06:43.846 --> 00:06:44.816 A:middle
glanceable information.

00:06:45.216 --> 00:06:47.756 A:middle
And, of course when your platter

00:06:47.756 --> 00:06:48.666 A:middle
is tapped, the underlying

00:06:48.666 --> 00:06:49.706 A:middle
shortcut will be executed.

00:06:50.056 --> 00:06:51.106 A:middle
So, let's take a look at how

00:06:51.106 --> 00:06:52.186 A:middle
this will run on this watch

00:06:52.186 --> 00:06:52.476 A:middle
face.

00:06:53.006 --> 00:06:54.976 A:middle
If your shortcut is backed by a

00:06:54.976 --> 00:06:56.226 A:middle
user activity, when the user

00:06:56.226 --> 00:06:57.916 A:middle
taps on it, your app will be

00:06:57.916 --> 00:07:00.136 A:middle
launched into the appropriate

00:06:57.916 --> 00:07:00.136 A:middle
launched into the appropriate

00:07:00.136 --> 00:07:00.726 A:middle
context.

00:07:01.256 --> 00:07:03.756 A:middle
If instead, your app is-- or,

00:07:03.756 --> 00:07:04.886 A:middle
your shortcut is based off of

00:07:04.886 --> 00:07:06.316 A:middle
intents, when the user taps on

00:07:06.316 --> 00:07:07.476 A:middle
the platter, we'll see this

00:07:07.476 --> 00:07:08.516 A:middle
intent confirmation view.

00:07:09.336 --> 00:07:10.556 A:middle
And, if they tap to confirm it,

00:07:11.156 --> 00:07:11.906 A:middle
if your intent runs at the

00:07:11.906 --> 00:07:13.106 A:middle
background, we'll execute it

00:07:13.106 --> 00:07:13.536 A:middle
inline.

00:07:14.576 --> 00:07:15.906 A:middle
If instead your intent can't run

00:07:15.906 --> 00:07:16.976 A:middle
in the background, we'll launch

00:07:16.976 --> 00:07:18.166 A:middle
your application, and hand you

00:07:18.166 --> 00:07:19.156 A:middle
the intent to continue

00:07:19.156 --> 00:07:19.716 A:middle
execution.

00:07:21.216 --> 00:07:22.556 A:middle
So, let's look at the API for

00:07:22.556 --> 00:07:23.306 A:middle
Relevant Shortcuts.

00:07:23.916 --> 00:07:25.146 A:middle
At the core of a relevant

00:07:25.146 --> 00:07:25.976 A:middle
shortcut, of course, is a

00:07:25.976 --> 00:07:26.396 A:middle
shortcut.

00:07:26.886 --> 00:07:28.286 A:middle
If you want to give us hints as

00:07:28.286 --> 00:07:29.086 A:middle
to when this content is

00:07:29.086 --> 00:07:30.166 A:middle
relevant, you can provide us

00:07:30.166 --> 00:07:31.256 A:middle
relevanceProviders, which we'll

00:07:31.256 --> 00:07:31.806 A:middle
go over soon.

00:07:33.196 --> 00:07:34.186 A:middle
And, if you want to customize

00:07:34.186 --> 00:07:36.216 A:middle
the UI beyond what your shortcut

00:07:36.216 --> 00:07:37.916 A:middle
will provide, you can give us a

00:07:37.916 --> 00:07:39.196 A:middle
defaultCardTemplate on the

00:07:39.196 --> 00:07:40.106 A:middle
watchTemplate property.

00:07:40.726 --> 00:07:43.246 A:middle
Now, once you're done creating

00:07:43.246 --> 00:07:44.166 A:middle
all of your wonderful relevant

00:07:44.166 --> 00:07:45.146 A:middle
shortcuts, you need to let us

00:07:45.146 --> 00:07:45.676 A:middle
know about them.

00:07:45.926 --> 00:07:46.886 A:middle
So, you want to inform the

00:07:46.886 --> 00:07:48.186 A:middle
default relevantShortcutStore.

00:07:48.696 --> 00:07:49.696 A:middle
And, the way you do that is

00:07:49.696 --> 00:07:50.576 A:middle
providing an array.

00:07:50.966 --> 00:07:52.066 A:middle
And, every time you give us an

00:07:52.066 --> 00:07:53.286 A:middle
array, it'll erase the previous

00:07:53.286 --> 00:07:54.596 A:middle
contents we had in our shortcut

00:07:54.596 --> 00:07:55.946 A:middle
store, which is really useful

00:07:55.946 --> 00:07:57.246 A:middle
for invalidating stale relevant

00:07:57.246 --> 00:07:57.786 A:middle
shortcuts.

00:07:58.116 --> 00:07:58.846 A:middle
But, you just need to keep in

00:07:58.846 --> 00:08:00.406 A:middle
mind to provide us all of the

00:07:58.846 --> 00:08:00.406 A:middle
mind to provide us all of the

00:08:00.406 --> 00:08:01.616 A:middle
relevant shortcuts we should be

00:08:01.616 --> 00:08:02.136 A:middle
considering.

00:08:03.876 --> 00:08:05.116 A:middle
So, let's look at how your

00:08:05.116 --> 00:08:05.946 A:middle
content will display on the

00:08:05.946 --> 00:08:06.266 A:middle
platter.

00:08:06.806 --> 00:08:08.296 A:middle
You can see on the top left,

00:08:08.296 --> 00:08:09.436 A:middle
your application's icon will be

00:08:09.436 --> 00:08:10.356 A:middle
displayed, followed by your

00:08:10.356 --> 00:08:10.836 A:middle
app's name.

00:08:11.536 --> 00:08:12.816 A:middle
Below that is a required title

00:08:12.816 --> 00:08:14.346 A:middle
string, and below that is an

00:08:14.346 --> 00:08:15.746 A:middle
optional subtitle string, that

00:08:15.746 --> 00:08:17.026 A:middle
you can use for more context.

00:08:17.386 --> 00:08:18.556 A:middle
We'll display that in italics.

00:08:19.236 --> 00:08:20.166 A:middle
To the left of both of these

00:08:20.166 --> 00:08:21.746 A:middle
strings is an optional custom

00:08:21.746 --> 00:08:22.106 A:middle
image.

00:08:22.646 --> 00:08:23.486 A:middle
This image supports

00:08:23.486 --> 00:08:24.836 A:middle
transparency, and automatically

00:08:24.836 --> 00:08:25.916 A:middle
applies rounded corners.

00:08:26.776 --> 00:08:27.696 A:middle
You can see more about the

00:08:27.696 --> 00:08:28.886 A:middle
dimensions of these assets by

00:08:29.086 --> 00:08:30.186 A:middle
looking at the human interface

00:08:30.186 --> 00:08:31.196 A:middle
guidelines resources for

00:08:31.196 --> 00:08:31.756 A:middle
watchOS.

00:08:32.496 --> 00:08:33.716 A:middle
Now, as I mentioned, we can

00:08:33.775 --> 00:08:35.096 A:middle
automatically populate all these

00:08:35.096 --> 00:08:35.966 A:middle
fields based off of the

00:08:35.966 --> 00:08:36.796 A:middle
shortcuts you supply.

00:08:37.196 --> 00:08:39.346 A:middle
In the case of a custom intent,

00:08:39.936 --> 00:08:41.426 A:middle
every parameter combination you

00:08:41.426 --> 00:08:43.265 A:middle
supply has an associated title

00:08:43.265 --> 00:08:44.246 A:middle
and subtitle we can use.

00:08:45.546 --> 00:08:46.556 A:middle
And, as you create your intents

00:08:46.556 --> 00:08:48.196 A:middle
in code to generate a shortcut,

00:08:48.856 --> 00:08:50.076 A:middle
you can set an image for any of

00:08:50.076 --> 00:08:50.766 A:middle
the parameters.

00:08:51.406 --> 00:08:52.606 A:middle
We will choose an image for the

00:08:52.606 --> 00:08:54.266 A:middle
custom image, based off of what

00:08:54.266 --> 00:08:55.536 A:middle
is available on the most

00:08:55.536 --> 00:08:56.436 A:middle
specific parameter.

00:08:57.326 --> 00:08:58.346 A:middle
And, the specificity of a

00:08:58.346 --> 00:08:59.356 A:middle
parameter is defined by the

00:08:59.416 --> 00:09:00.706 A:middle
order of parameters you have

00:08:59.416 --> 00:09:00.706 A:middle
order of parameters you have

00:09:00.706 --> 00:09:01.576 A:middle
listed in your intents

00:09:01.576 --> 00:09:02.256 A:middle
definition file.

00:09:02.836 --> 00:09:05.106 A:middle
In the case of an

00:09:05.106 --> 00:09:06.906 A:middle
NSUserActivity, when you're

00:09:06.906 --> 00:09:07.926 A:middle
creating your userActivity to

00:09:07.926 --> 00:09:09.536 A:middle
make a shortcut, you'll supply

00:09:09.536 --> 00:09:10.896 A:middle
it-- userActivity type that

00:09:10.896 --> 00:09:11.776 A:middle
you've listed in your app's

00:09:11.776 --> 00:09:12.776 A:middle
info.plist.

00:09:13.156 --> 00:09:13.986 A:middle
And, for us to be able to

00:09:13.986 --> 00:09:15.076 A:middle
display it without a default

00:09:15.076 --> 00:09:16.116 A:middle
card template, you'll need to

00:09:16.116 --> 00:09:17.176 A:middle
give us a title on the title

00:09:17.176 --> 00:09:17.596 A:middle
property.

00:09:18.646 --> 00:09:20.486 A:middle
In iOS you can also supply a

00:09:20.486 --> 00:09:22.526 A:middle
subtitle and a custom image by

00:09:22.526 --> 00:09:22.896 A:middle
creating a

00:09:22.896 --> 00:09:25.066 A:middle
CSSearchableItemAttributeSet.

00:09:26.256 --> 00:09:27.336 A:middle
And, on that attribute set,

00:09:27.336 --> 00:09:28.666 A:middle
we'll extract a subtitle from

00:09:28.666 --> 00:09:29.456 A:middle
the content description

00:09:29.456 --> 00:09:31.146 A:middle
property, and the custom image

00:09:31.146 --> 00:09:32.306 A:middle
from the thumbnailData property.

00:09:33.476 --> 00:09:34.426 A:middle
When you're done configuring

00:09:34.426 --> 00:09:35.926 A:middle
this attribute set, set on your

00:09:35.966 --> 00:09:36.926 A:middle
NSUserActivity's

00:09:37.066 --> 00:09:38.336 A:middle
contentAttributeSet property.

00:09:38.916 --> 00:09:42.216 A:middle
If you don't want to give us the

00:09:42.216 --> 00:09:43.856 A:middle
content that's baked into your

00:09:43.856 --> 00:09:44.846 A:middle
shortcut, you can supply a

00:09:44.846 --> 00:09:46.306 A:middle
default card template, which has

00:09:46.306 --> 00:09:47.156 A:middle
properties for each of the

00:09:47.156 --> 00:09:48.066 A:middle
fields on this platter.

00:09:48.536 --> 00:09:49.376 A:middle
And, depending on what we have

00:09:49.376 --> 00:09:51.106 A:middle
available to us, we will display

00:09:51.136 --> 00:09:51.796 A:middle
a different layout.

00:09:52.536 --> 00:09:53.296 A:middle
You can see in the right two

00:09:53.296 --> 00:09:54.746 A:middle
configurations, that if no image

00:09:54.746 --> 00:09:55.796 A:middle
is provided, we'll lay out the

00:09:55.796 --> 00:09:57.296 A:middle
text further to the left, giving

00:09:57.296 --> 00:09:58.696 A:middle
you more space for your words.

00:09:59.376 --> 00:10:00.836 A:middle
In the bottom two cases, if

00:09:59.376 --> 00:10:00.836 A:middle
In the bottom two cases, if

00:10:00.836 --> 00:10:02.126 A:middle
there's no subtitle, we'll allow

00:10:02.126 --> 00:10:03.206 A:middle
the title string to wrap from

00:10:03.206 --> 00:10:04.330 A:middle
the top line to the bottom line.

00:10:06.616 --> 00:10:08.796 A:middle
If your shortcut is based on an

00:10:08.796 --> 00:10:10.246 A:middle
intent, when a user taps on it,

00:10:10.246 --> 00:10:11.146 A:middle
they'll see this intent

00:10:11.146 --> 00:10:11.906 A:middle
confirmation view.

00:10:12.736 --> 00:10:13.546 A:middle
In the top left is your

00:10:13.546 --> 00:10:14.736 A:middle
application's icon, which is a

00:10:14.736 --> 00:10:15.946 A:middle
bit bigger this time, followed

00:10:15.946 --> 00:10:16.666 A:middle
by your app's name.

00:10:17.376 --> 00:10:18.416 A:middle
Below that we'll display the

00:10:18.416 --> 00:10:19.936 A:middle
title and subtitle directly from

00:10:19.936 --> 00:10:21.026 A:middle
your intents definition file.

00:10:21.626 --> 00:10:22.816 A:middle
And, at this point, the user has

00:10:22.886 --> 00:10:23.516 A:middle
three options.

00:10:24.186 --> 00:10:25.286 A:middle
If they want to run your intent,

00:10:25.556 --> 00:10:26.716 A:middle
they can click Confirm in that

00:10:26.716 --> 00:10:27.566 A:middle
middle pink button.

00:10:28.126 --> 00:10:28.996 A:middle
If they don't want to run it,

00:10:29.276 --> 00:10:30.406 A:middle
they can tap dismiss or the

00:10:30.406 --> 00:10:30.976 A:middle
digital crown.

00:10:31.496 --> 00:10:32.596 A:middle
And then, the third option is a

00:10:32.596 --> 00:10:33.266 A:middle
bit more subtle.

00:10:33.936 --> 00:10:35.486 A:middle
Sometimes users see an intent,

00:10:35.756 --> 00:10:37.076 A:middle
realize they want to tweak some

00:10:37.076 --> 00:10:37.886 A:middle
of the parameters.

00:10:38.176 --> 00:10:40.426 A:middle
So, they can tap that top

00:10:40.456 --> 00:10:41.926 A:middle
module, and we'll launch into

00:10:41.926 --> 00:10:43.276 A:middle
your application, and hand you

00:10:43.276 --> 00:10:44.486 A:middle
the intent you've customized.

00:10:44.726 --> 00:10:46.146 A:middle
So, you can present some UI to

00:10:46.146 --> 00:10:47.376 A:middle
allow your users to tweak some

00:10:47.376 --> 00:10:48.376 A:middle
of the parameters before

00:10:48.376 --> 00:10:49.356 A:middle
continuing execution.

00:10:50.666 --> 00:10:51.616 A:middle
Now, let's talk about that

00:10:51.616 --> 00:10:53.166 A:middle
middle pink Confirm button a

00:10:53.166 --> 00:10:55.186 A:middle
little bit more.

00:10:55.386 --> 00:10:56.306 A:middle
The string we show there, where

00:10:56.306 --> 00:10:57.806 A:middle
it says Action Verb, is derived

00:10:57.806 --> 00:10:58.976 A:middle
based off of the category of

00:10:58.976 --> 00:11:00.346 A:middle
intent you've defined in your

00:10:58.976 --> 00:11:00.346 A:middle
intent you've defined in your

00:11:00.346 --> 00:11:01.296 A:middle
intents definition file.

00:11:02.596 --> 00:11:04.336 A:middle
Additionally, that color is

00:11:04.336 --> 00:11:05.706 A:middle
chosen from your application's

00:11:05.706 --> 00:11:07.266 A:middle
global tint color in your watch

00:11:07.266 --> 00:11:08.056 A:middle
app storyboard.

00:11:08.666 --> 00:11:10.886 A:middle
Now, it's very important to keep

00:11:10.886 --> 00:11:11.946 A:middle
in mind that the intents that

00:11:11.976 --> 00:11:13.226 A:middle
you support in your watch app

00:11:13.276 --> 00:11:14.816 A:middle
must be a subset of the intents

00:11:14.816 --> 00:11:15.686 A:middle
you support in your iOS

00:11:15.686 --> 00:11:16.206 A:middle
application.

00:11:16.686 --> 00:11:17.406 A:middle
That means you're going to be

00:11:17.406 --> 00:11:19.066 A:middle
sharing the same title strings,

00:11:19.066 --> 00:11:21.196 A:middle
and subtitle strings on iOS and

00:11:21.196 --> 00:11:21.836 A:middle
watchOS.

00:11:22.306 --> 00:11:23.356 A:middle
And, watchOS is a very

00:11:23.356 --> 00:11:24.316 A:middle
constrained canvas.

00:11:24.536 --> 00:11:25.446 A:middle
Every word counts.

00:11:25.936 --> 00:11:27.426 A:middle
So, we highly recommend using

00:11:27.426 --> 00:11:28.776 A:middle
string dictionaries, with the

00:11:28.776 --> 00:11:30.666 A:middle
NSStringVariableWidthRuleType

00:11:30.726 --> 00:11:30.956 A:middle
key.

00:11:31.476 --> 00:11:32.636 A:middle
That allows you to give us a

00:11:32.636 --> 00:11:34.356 A:middle
list of varying sizes of strings

00:11:34.446 --> 00:11:35.296 A:middle
that we can choose from,

00:11:35.456 --> 00:11:36.456 A:middle
depending on the context we're

00:11:36.456 --> 00:11:37.096 A:middle
displaying them in.

00:11:38.456 --> 00:11:39.496 A:middle
When providing content to

00:11:39.496 --> 00:11:41.876 A:middle
watchOS, we recommend supplying

00:11:41.876 --> 00:11:43.776 A:middle
a string with a width rule of 20

00:11:44.166 --> 00:11:45.616 A:middle
for a 38 millimeter watch.

00:11:45.656 --> 00:11:47.506 A:middle
And, a width rule of 24 for a 42

00:11:47.506 --> 00:11:48.106 A:middle
millimeter watch.

00:11:48.756 --> 00:11:51.266 A:middle
To get more information on

00:11:51.266 --> 00:11:53.216 A:middle
adopting this API, please see

00:11:53.216 --> 00:11:54.476 A:middle
the "Localizing with Xcode 9"

00:11:54.476 --> 00:11:55.166 A:middle
talk from last year's

00:11:55.166 --> 00:11:55.706 A:middle
conference.

00:11:56.646 --> 00:11:58.726 A:middle
So now, let's talk about

00:11:58.726 --> 00:11:59.566 A:middle
relevance providers.

00:12:01.116 --> 00:12:02.676 A:middle
Relevance providers are your way

00:12:02.676 --> 00:12:04.146 A:middle
to give us a hint as to when we

00:12:04.146 --> 00:12:05.116 A:middle
should show your content.

00:12:06.436 --> 00:12:07.366 A:middle
They really let us know how we

00:12:07.366 --> 00:12:08.686 A:middle
should incorporate inputs like

00:12:08.716 --> 00:12:09.966 A:middle
the time of day, the user's

00:12:09.966 --> 00:12:11.536 A:middle
location, or their routine, when

00:12:11.536 --> 00:12:12.506 A:middle
calculating relevance.

00:12:13.186 --> 00:12:14.166 A:middle
And, in fact, you can give more

00:12:14.166 --> 00:12:15.366 A:middle
than one relevance provider on a

00:12:15.366 --> 00:12:16.266 A:middle
given relevance shortcut.

00:12:16.306 --> 00:12:17.526 A:middle
And, we're going to take the

00:12:17.526 --> 00:12:18.686 A:middle
inner section of their output.

00:12:19.016 --> 00:12:20.076 A:middle
So, if you give us a relevance

00:12:20.076 --> 00:12:21.286 A:middle
provider that says a certain

00:12:21.286 --> 00:12:22.296 A:middle
time of day's very important.

00:12:22.296 --> 00:12:23.336 A:middle
And, another one that says a

00:12:23.336 --> 00:12:24.606 A:middle
specific location's important,

00:12:25.116 --> 00:12:26.256 A:middle
you'll get high relevance output

00:12:26.356 --> 00:12:28.136 A:middle
when both it is that time of day

00:12:28.206 --> 00:12:29.296 A:middle
and the user is at that

00:12:29.296 --> 00:12:29.806 A:middle
location.

00:12:30.586 --> 00:12:31.866 A:middle
If instead you want the union of

00:12:31.866 --> 00:12:32.816 A:middle
these relevance providers,

00:12:32.816 --> 00:12:33.756 A:middle
you're going to want to provide

00:12:33.906 --> 00:12:35.356 A:middle
two separate relevance

00:12:35.356 --> 00:12:36.356 A:middle
shortcuts, each one with a

00:12:36.356 --> 00:12:37.246 A:middle
different relevance provider.

00:12:37.746 --> 00:12:39.716 A:middle
So, let's take a look at the

00:12:39.716 --> 00:12:40.586 A:middle
options we have available.

00:12:41.416 --> 00:12:42.246 A:middle
The first one is

00:12:42.436 --> 00:12:44.726 A:middle
INDateRelevanceProvider, which

00:12:44.726 --> 00:12:45.656 A:middle
has a required startDate

00:12:45.656 --> 00:12:46.876 A:middle
parameter, and an optional

00:12:46.876 --> 00:12:47.536 A:middle
endDate parameter.

00:12:48.546 --> 00:12:49.516 A:middle
When you create an instance of

00:12:49.516 --> 00:12:50.986 A:middle
this relevance provider, the

00:12:50.986 --> 00:12:52.416 A:middle
closer time of day gets to the

00:12:52.536 --> 00:12:53.676 A:middle
start that you've provided, the

00:12:53.676 --> 00:12:54.866 A:middle
higher the relevance output of

00:12:54.866 --> 00:12:55.346 A:middle
the provider.

00:12:56.226 --> 00:12:57.596 A:middle
After that time of day passes,

00:12:57.836 --> 00:12:58.856 A:middle
the relevance will fall off on a

00:12:58.856 --> 00:13:00.126 A:middle
curve, allowing more content to

00:12:58.856 --> 00:13:00.126 A:middle
curve, allowing more content to

00:13:00.126 --> 00:13:01.046 A:middle
appear on the top of the watch

00:13:01.046 --> 00:13:01.366 A:middle
face.

00:13:01.706 --> 00:13:02.466 A:middle
And, if you give us this

00:13:02.466 --> 00:13:04.076 A:middle
optional endDate, we'll adjust

00:13:04.076 --> 00:13:05.316 A:middle
that curve to accommodate.

00:13:05.856 --> 00:13:08.806 A:middle
If your content instead is more

00:13:08.806 --> 00:13:10.086 A:middle
relevant to a given location,

00:13:10.086 --> 00:13:10.706 A:middle
you can use the

00:13:10.816 --> 00:13:12.076 A:middle
INLocationRelevanceProvider.

00:13:13.086 --> 00:13:14.916 A:middle
It takes a CLRegion as its main

00:13:14.916 --> 00:13:16.246 A:middle
parameter when you create an

00:13:16.246 --> 00:13:16.956 A:middle
instance of this.

00:13:17.116 --> 00:13:18.296 A:middle
As the user gets closer and

00:13:18.296 --> 00:13:19.686 A:middle
closer to that region, the

00:13:19.686 --> 00:13:20.666 A:middle
relevance output of this

00:13:20.666 --> 00:13:21.936 A:middle
relevanceProvider gets higher

00:13:21.936 --> 00:13:22.306 A:middle
and higher.

00:13:23.686 --> 00:13:24.956 A:middle
Now, you don't always have a

00:13:24.956 --> 00:13:26.246 A:middle
specific time of day, or

00:13:26.246 --> 00:13:27.506 A:middle
location in mind, for where your

00:13:27.506 --> 00:13:29.946 A:middle
content should be relevant.

00:13:30.296 --> 00:13:31.866 A:middle
User's schedules, their favorite

00:13:31.866 --> 00:13:33.676 A:middle
locations vary all over the

00:13:33.676 --> 00:13:34.636 A:middle
place, and you don't want to

00:13:34.636 --> 00:13:35.796 A:middle
have to get in the business of

00:13:35.796 --> 00:13:36.546 A:middle
tracking all of this.

00:13:36.736 --> 00:13:38.126 A:middle
So, you can take advantage of

00:13:38.126 --> 00:13:39.596 A:middle
the Siri face's smarts, and use

00:13:39.596 --> 00:13:39.676 A:middle
an

00:13:39.836 --> 00:13:41.226 A:middle
INDailyRoutineRelevanceProvider,

00:13:41.496 --> 00:13:42.646 A:middle
where we have situations for

00:13:42.646 --> 00:13:43.856 A:middle
both time of days that might be

00:13:43.856 --> 00:13:45.116 A:middle
favorite for your users, and

